ke the abuse with a smile on their face, & do not dare question it\\u2026or else.https://t.co/ZXKtfJEOcO  It came as a surprise to no one.  Wow. I am so shocked that someone with XY chromosomes beat a biological female.https://t.co/KLAc8QCTnh  Some were happy that a male beat all the women and took the medal, because it will 'rile up conservatives' and people who just know what a woman is.  Conservatives fuming right now lmfaooohttps://t.co/zyzGaZRrse  Sooo good ?It'll rile up the Andrew Tate and Piers Morgan side of Twitterhttps://t.co/iVeBfb7GvL  As we previously highlighted, the\\u00a0International Boxing Association\\u00a0(IBA) held a press conference earlier in the week in Paris and categorically confirmed that Khelif and Taiwan's Lin Yu-Ting, who will undoubtedly win a gold medal today, are \\\"male\\\" by definition of medical science because they failed previous gender chromosome tests that determine who is allowed to compete in the women's category.  Dr. Ioannis Filippatos, the former Chair of the IBA Medical Committee, was adamant that the fighters should not be competing as women, stating \\\"Medicine is knowledge, it is not opinion,\\\" and adding \\\"The nature and the biological world do not change.\\\"  In addition, Istvan Kovacs, the European vice president of the World Boxing Organization (WBO), has also publicly asserted that Khelif is biologically male.  \\\"The saddest thing in the story is that the problem was not with the level of Khelif's testosterone, because it can be adjusted nowadays, but with the result of the gender test, which clearly revealed that the Algerian boxer is biologically male,\\\" he said.  The International Olympic Committee has defended its decision to allow both boxers to compete throughout the games, with the president claiming on Friday that no solid scientific system exists on how to identify men and women.  NEW - IOC president says there is no solid scientific system on how to identify men and women.pic.twitter.com/Vd